        "id": "bk-job",
        "q": "Summarize the book of Job: author, date, theme, and outline.",
        "a": "**Author & date.** Author unknown; the events are patriarchal in flavor (wealth measured in livestock, Job acting as family priest), so many place the setting in the patriarchal era, with composition possibly under Solomon's wisdom flourishing (c. 10th century B.C.) or earlier.\n\n**Genre.** Wisdom; mostly poetic dialogue framed by prose narrative.\n\n**Theme.** Why the righteous suffer, and whether God may be trusted and worshiped for His own sake rather than for blessings. The book answers not with tidy explanations but with God Himself, who is sovereign, wise, and beyond human cross-examination.\n\n**Outline.**\n- 1–2 — Prologue: Job's testing in the heavenly court\n- 3 — Job's lament\n- 4–27 — Three cycles of debate with the friends\n- 28–31 — Wisdom hymn and Job's final defense\n- 32–37 — Elihu's speeches\n- 38–42 — The LORD answers; Job's repentance and restoration\n\n**Christ & significance.** Job longs for a mediator and living Redeemer (9:33; 19:25), a cry answered fully in Christ, the truly innocent sufferer whose vindication secures ours.",
